  					<td align=center valign="top" width=100%><br>
  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - BARD</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>BRAVE SIR ROBIN BRAVELY RAN AWAY...</font> - <small>Kayfess Trevallin, Bertoxxulous</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>From your earliest of days, you've been named for wimp and coward, especially once you learn't to play <i>Selo's Accelerando</i>. 'Run away, little bard', people shout. <P>

Hopefully, you have invested a little time in the careful use of <i>Brass Instruments</i> so that you don't drop every second note when you try to sing <i>Dennon's</i> or the <i>Screech</i>. <P>

You may have noticed, by now, that you were never mean't to be hit. It's just not becoming of a bard to have some inappreciative audience physically intervening with your performance. <P>

Once you have the <i>Screech</i>, a whole new era dawns before you. Finally you can turn the audience. The <i>Screech</i> is so appalling that your listeners will run away. The trick is, to make sure they don't run away at full speed with <i>Selo's Consonant Chain</i>. "Snare and Fear", they call it. And twist in either heal, discord or anthem... <P>

The added bonus of using the <i>Consonant Chain</i> is that it affects your victims speed of attack, which makes it greatly advantageous over singing <i>Accellerando</i> and <i>Screech</i>. <P>

Now, whilst I am amazed if any bard makes it past their 30th song without learning this skill, and I laugh at the bards who make it past 45 without it (and I have met some, though I struggle to call these bards), I have met few who know how to use this tactic within a dungeon. <P>

The <i>Screech</i>, as you should know, has a <b>very</b> short range. The listener is generally only afeared when you shout the song directly into their ear (or other olifactory orifice). <P>

This offers two possibilities of use in dungeon, or dungeon-like, situations. I primarily use this combination while aiding in derailing those awful pileups one often finds when entering a zone. This is a matter of skilled timing, since your next <i>Screech</i> needs to co-incide with the return of the angry mob. <P>

The other skill, and this is a hard come-by, hard learned skill, is in crowd control. At it's very simplest, your party assembles around you, and you snare the common victim, whilst fearing away the mob. With what might otherwise be considered a 'weak' party, I have fought my way through 6 spectres and seen the light of day on the far side (if a little bruised). <P>

In a more precarious situation, however, this is guaranteed to spell certain doom. You cannot simply employ this tactic in the depths of Lower Guk, or the Castle of Mayong Mistmoore. At least, not without skill and cunning... <P>

Of recent, I have been spending time in the tower, just off the castle. My group has on occasion become overwhelmed, and typically our healer becomes the target of many foul dark-elves. Against all instructions or common-wisdom, I have employed fear in these situations, and our party has prevailed. <P>

With our druid under twin attacks, whilst the party mele'd amongst another throng, I detached myself to the far side of the druid and her foes, snared the one whilst she snared t'other, and sang my <i>screech</i> from just within range. The pair immediately left the druid be, and began slowly to walk away, giving our druid time to heal and such, whilst I gained chance to sing once more to my party, and enter a little mele. <P>

When they regained their will, they returned, not to our druid, but to myself. And by withdrawing a short way from the frenzy, I was able to repeat this process. <P>

However, had they been unsnared, they would likely have reached friends and brought them back with them. The important side to this skill is to learn the range of your <i>screech</i> and to make sure you sing it to nothing that can truly run. It often helps to sing a fresh chorus of <i>consonant chain</i> or <i>pixie strike</i> to your victim once their back is turned.<p>

So; remember, that Brave Sir Robin Bravely Ran Away, and that 'Fear and Snare' is a highly adaptable skill, as is most of our Bardic Repetoire. Learn it well, and may Bristlebane grant you every success.<p>


Kayfess Trevallin,<br>
<i>The Company</i>,<br>
Bertoxxulous</td></tr>
